<h1>Problem 2315 - 2016 Indian TST, Day 4, P2 of 3</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 7</h2>
<p>Find all functions \(f:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}\) such that
\[f\left(x^3+f(y)\right)=x^2f(x)+y,\]
for all \(x,y\in\mathbb{R}.\) (Here \(\mathbb{R}\) denotes the set of all real numbers.)</p>
<h2>Thinking</h2>
<div class = skib>
<p>Instantly obtain from \(P(0, y)\) that \(f(f(y)) = y\), so \(f\) is bijective and we can substitute \(f\)s. Suppose \(f(k) = 0\). Then \(P(k, y)\) gives \(f(k^3 + f(y)) = y =f(f(y))\), which means \(k = 0\). \(P(x, f(y))\) gives
\[f(x^3 + y)= x^2f(x) + f(y)\]
So \(f(x^3) = x^2 f(x)\). Substituting \(y = f(-x^3)\) gives \(-f(-x^3) = x^2f(x) = f(x^3)\), which means \(f(-x) = -f(x)\). We have the equation
\[f(x^3 + y) = f(x^3) + f(y) \implies f(x + y) = f(x) + f(y)\]
\[(x^2 + y^2 + 2xy)(f(x) + f(y)) = (x+y)^2f(x+y) = f((x+y)^3) = f(x^3) + f(y^3) + 3f(x^2y) + 3f(xy^2)\]
\[x^2f(y) + y^2f(x) + 2xyf(x) + 2xyf(y) = 3f(x^2y) + 3f(xy^2)\]
Adding \(Q(x, y)\) and \(Q(x, -y)\) in this new equation yields
\[y^2f(x) + 2xyf(y) = 3f(xy^2) \implies y^2f(1) + 2yf(y) = 3f(y^2)\]
But \(Q(1, y)\) gives
\[y^2f(1) + 2yf(1) + 2yf(y) = 2f(y) + 3f(y^2)\]
So we get \(f(y) = yf(1)\). Upon checking, the functions \(f(x) = x\) and \(f(x) = -x\) work.
</p>
</div>
<h2>Idea</h2>
<p>Suppose you have Cauchy and some other condition. Then you want to force some sort of generalized version of this other condition onto Cauchy so that you can `<b>double-count</b>' some quantity.</p>
